# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wales
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The **1904–1905 Welsh revival** was the largest Christian revival in Wales during the 20th century.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] It was one of the most dramatic in terms of its effect on the population, and triggered revivals in several other countries.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The movement kept the churches of Wales filled for many years to come, seats being placed in the aisles in Mount Pleasant Baptist Church in Swansea for twenty years or so, for example.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Meanwhile, the awakening swept the rest of Britain, Scandinavia, parts of Europe, North America, the mission fields of India and the Orient, Africa and Latin America.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The Welsh revival has been traced as the root of the megachurches in the present era.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The last revival in Wales was in 1859, but this followed other developments.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] From 1850 onwards, Christianity in Wales was markedly less Calvinistic in form.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] A generation of powerful biblical preachers ended, as leaders such as Christmas Evans (1766–1838), John Elias (1744–1841) and Henry Rees (1798–1869) died.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Between 1859 and 1904, there were local revivals in Cwmafan (1866), Rhondda (1879), Carmarthen and Blaenau Ffestiniog (1887), Dowlais (1890) and Pontnewydd (1892).
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] A prominent leader of the Revival was the Methodist preacher of New Quay, Joseph Jenkins, who arranged a conference in New Quay in 1903 with the theme to deepen loyalty to Christ.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] During a meeting in February 1904, Florrie Evans is quoted as having said, "I love Jesus Christ with all my heart", a statement which is recognized as having made an impression on the attendees.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] This event supposedly initiated the revival.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The regular Sunday meetings, as well as the newly founded midweek meetings, became lively.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Members of Joseph Jenkins' church, led by Jenkins, traveled to other nearby towns and villages.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In September, a conference was held at Blaenannerch.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] It was reported that 'massive blessing' was upon this conference and the news quickly spread throughout the area and beyond.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The *South Wales Daily News* picked up on the events and reported that "the third great revival was afoot through the nation!".
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The other two noted revivals were the Welsh Methodist revival and the 1859 Methodist revival.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In November 1904, Jenkins was invited to be a guest preacher at meetings in Bethany, Ammanford, the church of Nantlais Williams.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] When the appointment was arranged, there was no news yet of the conversions in New Quay and Blaenannerch, but an extra meeting was hastily arranged on the Sunday afternoon so that Joseph Jenkins could tell about the events.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Williams is recorded to have said that he was worried that there would be no interest in such a meeting and he was skeptical what the turnout would be.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] However, when he arrived, he could only just squeeze into the chapel to hear Jenkins.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] It had been arranged that Jenkins was to preach on the Monday night before his return to New Quay.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The church was again full with people professing their faith in Jesus.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Perhaps the most dramatic turn was when one of the crowd members announced, "Another meeting like this will be held here tomorrow night".
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] That meeting was also well attended and went on until the early hours of the next morning.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Despite already having been ordained as a minister, on that weekend in November 1904, Williams had a conversion experience, on the Saturday night prior to Jenkins' arrival.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In December 1904, Joseph Jenkins embarked on three months of preaching and professing in areas of North Wales.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Many meetings were held in Amlwch, Llangefni, Llanerchymedd, Talysarn, Llanllyfni, Llanrwst, Denbigh, and Dinorwig, and some students at the University of Wales Bangor were converted.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] But perhaps the most conversions were seen in Bethesda; another leader of the revival, J.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Job, described the meeting held in Jerusalem, Bethesda on 22 December 1904 as "a hurricane".
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Evan Roberts was a young man influenced by the stories and experiences that were happening in New Quay and Blaenannerch.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] He decided to go to Newcastle Emlyn for ministerial training, and arrived in the revival in south Ceredigion.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The news of the mass conversions in New Quay and Blaenannerch had already spread to Newcastle Emlyn and were a distraction for a man who had been sent there to study.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Seth Joshua, another prominent leader of the revival, was invited to preach locally at a youth rally in Newquay, which Roberts had been given permission by the bible school to attend.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Seth had been praying for many years for God to give him Wales.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] After Evan's three months training at Newcastle Emlyn he was to return to Loughor to start his ministry.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] He claimed to have direct visions from the Holy Spirit: very specific visions, such as the number 100,000 representing the souls God intended to use him to save.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] As the revival unfolded, Roberts is said to have depended increasingly upon what he considered the guidance of the Holy Spirit.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Response to Roberts' ministry was initially slow, but soon the crowds turned out and the meetings were carried on until the early hours of the morning.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] After the meeting at Loughor, Roberts assembled a team and went on a tour of the South Wales valleys to spread the revival.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Roberts did not take the decline of the revival well.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The great expectations of a worldwide revival that had arisen in his team were frustrated, and he afterwards fell into depression.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In 1913, when Roberts's mother was dying, his brother Dan tried to see him to ask him to visit his mother.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Eventually "Awstin", the reporter of the revival, gained access.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] There were rumours that Roberts was being held prisoner by the Penn-Lewises.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Roberts spoke freely about how God was preparing him for his next great work, and sent, via "Awstin", "God's message to the churches of south Wales".
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Because of Roberts's treatment of his mother, the message was ignored.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Aberdare became a major centre of the revival and the first area that Evan Roberts visited following his initial meetings at Loughor.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In the Aberdare area, the revival aroused alarm among ministers for the revolutionary, even anarchistic, impact it had upon chapel congregations and denominational organization.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] In particular, it was seen as drawing attention away from pulpit preaching and the role of the minister.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The local newspaper, the *Aberdare Leader*, regarded the revival with suspicion from the outset, objecting to the 'abnormal heat' which it engendered.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Trecynon was particularly affected by the revival, and the meetings held there were said to have aroused more emotion and excitement than the more restrained meetings in Aberdare itself.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The impact of the revival was significant in the short term, but in the longer term was fairly transient.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] For the first time, the newspapers had a role in this revival.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The *Western Mail* and the *South Wales Daily News*, Wales' daily newspapers, spread news of conversions and generated an air of excitement that helped to fuel the revival.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The *Western Mail* in particular gave extensive coverage to Roberts' meetings in Loughor.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The articles were gathered together and published as a series of seven pamphlets, including copies of picture postcards of the revivalists that were published at the time.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The contents of the final pamphlet are credited by some as killing the revival.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Peter Price, a minister from Dowlais, wrote a letter that was very critical of Evan Roberts.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Price wanted to distinguish between the genuine revival that he believed was going on and a sham revival he associated with Evan Roberts.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The pamphlet contains many letters in support of Evan Roberts (the majority), and a few supporting Price.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Vyrynwy Morgan gives further letters supporting Price.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The Welsh revival has been described not as an isolated religious movement, but as very much a part of Britain's modernisation.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The revival began in late 1904 under the leadership of Evan Roberts (1878–1951), a 26-year-old former collier and minister in training.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The revival lasted less than a year, but in that time 100,000 people were converted.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Begun as an effort to kindle non-denominational, non-sectarian spirituality, the Welsh revival of 1904–05 coincided with the rise of the labour movement, socialism, and a general disaffection with religion among the working class and youths.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Placed in context, the short-lived revival appears as both a climax for nonconformism and a flashpoint of change in Welsh religious life.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The movement spread to Scotland and England, with estimates that a million people were converted in Britain.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Missionaries subsequently carried the movement abroad; it was especially influential on the Pentecostal movement emerging in California.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] Unlike earlier religious revivals based on powerful preaching, the revival of 1904–05 relied primarily on music and on alleged supernatural phenomena as exemplified by the visions of Evan Roberts.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The intellectual emphasis of the earlier revivals had left a dearth of religious imagery that the visions supplied.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The visions also challenged the denial of the spiritual and miraculous element of Scripture by opponents of the revival, who held liberal and critical theological positions.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The structure and content of the visions not only repeated those of Scripture and earlier Christian mystical tradition but also illuminated the personal and social tensions that the revival addressed by juxtaposing Biblical images with scenes familiar to contemporary Welsh believers.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] The after-effects of the revival were considered by Vyrynwy Morgan in the final chapter of his book, which gives the figures for convictions for drunkenness in the county of Glamorgan for the years 1902 to 1907, supplied by the police.
[src:wales/1904-1905-welsh-revival] There is a near 50% reduction after the revival.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:wales/1958-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A post-legislative referendum was held in Scotland in 1979 to decide whether there was sufficient support among the Scottish electorate for a Scottish Assembly proposed in the Scotland Act 1978.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was an act to create a devolved deliberative assembly for Scotland.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A majority (51.6%) of voters supported the proposal, but an amendment to the Act stipulated that it would be repealed if less than 40% of the total electorate voted in favour.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] As there was a turnout of 64% the "Yes" vote represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate, and the act was subsequently repealed.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A second referendum to create a devolved legislature in Scotland was held in 1997 under a newly elected Labour government, which led to the enactment of the Scotland Act 1998 and the creation of a devolved Scottish Parliament in 1999.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The royal commission was intended to look at the constitutional structure of the United Kingdom and consider changes that should be made.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The commission examined various models of devolution, federalism and confederalism, on top of the break-up of the UK into separate sovereign states.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In relation to Scotland, eight of the commission's members supported a Scottish Assembly, via a devolved structure.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It would recommend that the assembly would have around 100 members, elected under single transferable vote from multi-member constituencies.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The assembly would obtain powers in the areas of education, environment, health, home affairs, legal matters and social services, while agriculture, fisheries and food would be divided between the assembly and the UK government.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After returning to power with a minority government in February 1974 election, Harold Wilson's Labour government published a white paper entitled *Democracy and Devolution: Proposals for Scotland and Wales*, published in September 1974.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The party gained a narrow majority of three seats in the election in October.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] By 1976, the Labour government, now led by James Callaghan, had lost its parliamentary majority entirely following a series of adverse by-election results.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The *Scotland and Wales Bill* was subsequently introduced in November 1976, but the government struggled to get the legislation through parliament.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Conservative opposition opposed its second reading, and on the first day of committee 350 amendments were put down.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In February 1977, the Bill's cabinet sponsor Michael Foot tabled a guillotine motion to attempt to halt the delays.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The motion was rejected and the government was forced to withdraw the Bill.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government returned to the issue of devolution in November 1977.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Separate bills for Scotland and Wales were published and support from the Liberals was obtained.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In spite of continued opposition requiring another guillotine motion, the Bills were passed.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] During the passage of the Scotland Act 1978 through Parliament, an amendment introduced by Labour MP George Cunningham added a requirement that the bill had to be approved by 40% of the total registered electorate, as well as a simple majority (50% + 1).
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The sample was made up of voters in Scotland and Wales.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Number of people who said they did not vote.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was a majority in favour of devolution.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A total of 1,230,937 (51.6%) voted at the referendum in favour of an Assembly, a majority of about 77,400 over those voting against.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, this total represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate as a whole.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Labour government held that the Act's requirements had not been met, and that devolution would therefore not be introduced for Scotland.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In the wake of the referendum the disappointed supporters of the bill conducted a protest campaign under the slogan "Scotland said 'yes'", officially launched in a Glasgow hotel on 7 March 1979.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In particular, the Scottish National Party (SNP) carried out a survey of the electoral register in the Edinburgh Central constituency.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This appeared to show that the register was so out of date that even in an area where major support for a "yes" vote might be expected, achievement of 40% of the electorate was virtually unattainable.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was because the majority of electors lived in older tenements or newer Council blocks of flats where flat numbers were not specified.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The work of electoral registration staff to obtain an accurate current register was almost impossible.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Under the terms of the Act, it could then be repealed by a Statutory instrument to be approved by Parliament.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government's decision to abandon devolution led the SNP to withdraw its support for the Labour government.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was in a minority in Parliament and had relied on deals with the smaller parties, including the SNP, for its survival.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After establishing that the Liberals and the SNP would vote against the government in a confidence motion, the Conservative opposition tabled a motion on 28 March.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government was defeated by one vote, and a UK general election was subsequently called.
[src:wales/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was won by the Conservatives, and Parliament voted to repeal the Act on 20 June 1979.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The **1979 Welsh devolution referendum** was a post-legislative referendum held on 1 March 1979 (Saint David's Day) to decide whether there was sufficient support for a Welsh Assembly among the Welsh electorate.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum was held under the terms of the Wales Act 1978 drawn up to implement proposals made by the Kilbrandon Report published in 1973.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The plans were defeated by a majority of 4:1 (20.3% for and 79.7% against) with only 12% of the Welsh electorate voting in favour of establishing an assembly.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] A second referendum to create a devolved assembly for Wales was held in 1997, which led to the enactment of the Government of Wales Act 1998 and the creation of the National Assembly for Wales in 1999.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Both the Scotland Act and the Wales Act contained a requirement that at least 40% of all voters back the plan.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] It had been passed as an amendment by Islington South MP George Cunningham with the backing of Bedwellty MP Neil Kinnock.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Kinnock, the future leader of the Labour Party, called himself a "unionist".
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] His stated view was that "between the mid-sixteenth century and the mid-eighteenth century Wales had practically no history at all, and even before that it was the history of rural brigands who have been ennobled by being called princes".
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] He was one of six south Wales Labour MPs who opposed their own Government's plans, along with Leo Abse (Pontypool), Donald Anderson (Swansea East), Ioan Evans (Aberdare), Fred Evans (Caerphilly), and Ifor Davies (Gower).
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The government of James Callaghan did not have an overall majority in the House of Commons, and was therefore vulnerable to opposition from within its own ranks.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour party was split on home rule for Wales with a vocal minority opposed.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] They considered devolution as a danger to the unity of the UK and a concession to Welsh nationalism in the wake of by-election victories by Plaid Cymru.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party committed itself to devolution after coming to power in the February 1974 General Election.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] It followed the findings of a Royal Commission on the Constitution under Lord Kilbrandon.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Set up in 1969 in the wake of pressure to address growing support for independence in Scotland and Wales it delivered a split report in 1973.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Royal Commission recommended legislative and executive devolution to Scotland and Wales, with a minority supporting advisory Regional Councils for England.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] This plan was rejected as too bureaucratic and ill-advised in economic terms.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] New plans were brought forward by Harold Wilson's government in 1975 and 1976 which confined devolution to Scotland and Wales.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Scotland and Wales Bill had a difficult passage through Parliament and the government, lacking a majority to pass the plan, withdrew the legislation and introduced separate Bills for Scotland and Wales.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Hostile Labour MPs from the north of England, Wales and Scotland combined to insist that Assemblies could only be passed if directly endorsed by voters in a post-legislative referendum.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] In 1978, John Morris, Baron Morris of Aberavon was under the impression that James Callaghan would call a general election in the autumn, but called it off.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] On 1 March, Saint David's Day, the devolution referendum was held but came at the end of the Winter of Discontent.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Factors such as "tribalism" divisions within Wales and impressions that a Welsh Assembly would be dominated by people of one particular region could have potentially caused the proposal to be rejected.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] According to John Morris, people in southern Wales were persuaded by the No campaign that the Assembly would be dominated by "bigoted Welsh-speakers from the north and the west" whilst in northern Wales, people had been convinced the Assembly would be a dominated Glamorgan County Council "Taffia".
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] These factors led to a failed devolution referendum.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Proposals for a more powerful Assembly in Scotland attracted the support of a majority of those who voted (1,230,937 for, 1,153,502 against) (see 1979 Scottish devolution referendum), but it amounted to just 32.5% of the total electorate, lower than the 40% threshold required.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The results sealed the fate of the minority Labour government, and as a direct result of the defeat of the referendums in Wales and Scotland the Scottish National Party (SNP) withdrew its support for the government, though Plaid Cymru supported the government in exchange for political concessions.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] In the House of Commons on 28 March 1979, the Labour government was defeated on a motion of no confidence by one vote, only the second time in the 20th century that a government was brought down in this way.
[src:wales/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Labour's defeat in the 1979 General Election to Margaret Thatcher's Conservative Party precipitated a civil war within its own ranks, and the party was to be out of office for eighteen years.
[src:wales/cymru] The TLD was proposed by the British internet registry company Nominet, which has run the domain for the UK (.uk) since 1996.
[src:wales/cymru] The proposal initially ran into conflict with .cym, proposed by the Wales-based, not-for-profit dotCYM organisation, which advocates for the Welsh language and culture.
[src:wales/cymru] In June 2014, final go-ahead for the domains was granted by ICANN, and a phased launch of the new domains began.
[src:wales/cymru] Initially, the new domains were available to trademark holders, with full availability originally planned for the spring of 2015.
[src:wales/cymru] On 30 September 2014, the Llywydd of the Senedd officially moved Senedd websites and other sites to new ".cymru" and ".wales" domains which are geographic top-level domains specific to Wales.
[src:wales/cymru] Wales Online, Daily Post, the Welsh Rugby Union, the Millennium Stadium, Golwg360, Bloc, Gwalia, Atlantic PLC, Orchard and Portmeirion were among others who also switched over to the domains.
[src:wales/cymru] These became available to all on St David's Day 2015.
[src:wales/gb] The domain was introduced with RFC 920 in October 1984 that set out the creation of ccTLD generally using country codes derived from the corresponding two-letter code in the ISO 3166-1 list.
[src:wales/gb] However, the .uk domain had been created separately a few months before the compilation of this list.
[src:wales/gb] Consequently, .gb was never widely used.
[src:wales/gb] It is no longer possible to register under this domain.
[src:wales/gb] .gb was used for a number of years, mainly by British government organisations and commercial e-mail services using X.400-based e-mail infrastructure.
[src:wales/gb] This simplified translating between DNS domains and X.400 addresses, which used "GB" as a country code.
[src:wales/gb] With the demise of X.400 e-mail and IANA's general aim of one TLD per country, use of .gb declined; the domain remains in existence, but it is not currently open to new domain registrations.
[src:wales/gb] As of 2025, there are at least three subdomains resolving through DNS (although none serve a web page or use): `hermes.dra.hmg.gb`, `delos.dra.hmg.gb`, and `dfhnet.dra.hmg.gb`.
[src:wales/gb] They were originally owned by the Defence Research Agency, which became the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency in 1995 and was split into QinetiQ and the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory in 2001; the websites became defunct some time thereafter.
[src:wales/gb] As of November 2022, Central Digital and Data Office's intention was to inform ICANN early in 2023 that the UK wishes to retire the .gb ccTLD.
[src:wales/uk] In October 1984, RFC 920 set out the creation of ccTLDs using country codes derived from the corresponding two-letter code in the ISO 3166-1 list.
[src:wales/uk] However, the UK academic network Name Registration Scheme, JANET NRS, had defined "UK" as the top-level domain a few months before the compilation of the ISO-derived list.
[src:wales/uk] Consequently, .uk was chosen and registered on 24 July 1985. .gb was reserved but never widely used and it is no longer possible to register domains under that ccTLD.
[src:wales/uk] As with other ccTLDs in the early days it was originally delegated by Jon Postel to a "trusted person" to manage.
[src:wales/uk] Andrew McDowell at UCL was assigned .uk, the first country code delegation.
[src:wales/uk] In time, he passed it to Willie Black at the UK Education and Research Networking Association (UKERNA).
[src:wales/uk] Originally, domain requests were emailed, manually screened by and then forwarded to the UK Naming Committee before being processed by UKERNA.
[src:wales/uk] Membership of this committee was restricted to a group of high-end ISPs who were part of a formal peering arrangement.
[src:wales/uk] The Naming Committee was organised as a mailing list to which all proposed names were circulated.
[src:wales/uk] The members would consider the proposals under a ruleset that insisted that all domain names should be very close if not identical to a registered business name of the registrant.
[src:wales/uk] Members of the Naming Committee could object to any name, and if at least a small number of objections were received, the name was refused.
[src:wales/uk] By the mid-1990s the growth of the Internet, and particularly the advent of the World Wide Web was pushing requests for domain name registrations up to levels that were not manageable by a group of part-time volunteers.
[src:wales/uk] Oliver Smith of Demon Internet forced the issue by providing the committee with a series of automated tools, called the "automaton", which formalised and automated the naming process end to end.
[src:wales/uk] This allowed many more registrations to be processed far more reliably and rapidly, and inspired individuals such as Ivan Pope to explore more entrepreneurial approaches to registration.
[src:wales/uk] Various plans were put forward for the possible management of the domain, mostly Internet service providers seeking to stake a claim, each of which were naturally unacceptable to the rest of the committee.
[src:wales/uk] In response to this Black, as the .uk Name, stepped up with a bold proposal for a not-for-profit commercial entity to deal with the .uk domain properly.
[src:wales/uk] Commercial interests initially balked at this, but with widespread support Nominet UK was formed in 1996 to be the .uk Network Information Centre, a role which it continues to this day.
[src:wales/uk] The general form of the rules (i.e. which domains can be registered and whether to allow second level domains) was set by the Naming Committee.
[src:wales/uk] Nominet has not made major changes to the rules, although it has introduced a new second level domain .me.uk for individuals.
[src:wales/uk] Until 10 June 2014 it was not possible to register a domain name directly under .uk (such as *internet.uk*); it was only possible as a third-level domain (such as *internet.co.uk*).
[src:wales/uk] Currently, management of the .uk domain name is delegated by IANA to Nominet UK.
[src:wales/uk] It is possible to directly register a domain name with Nominet UK at £80+VAT as of 2021, but it is faster and cheaper to do it via a Nominet-accredited domain registrar costing in the region of £10+VAT in 2021.
[src:wales/uk] If a domain was registered before 23:59 UTC on 28 October 2013 the user had the rights to the equivalent .uk domain (providing there was no other corresponding .co.uk, .org.uk, me.uk, .ltd.uk, .plc.uk or .net.uk registered).
[src:wales/uk] For example, if "your-company.co.uk" was held since 2 October 2013, the registrant of 'your-company.co.uk' had the reserved right of registering "your-company.uk", up until 06:00 BST on 25 June 2019.
[src:wales/uk] 123-reg and NamesCo both created such domains for their customers for free but then began demanding payment in September 2019.
[src:wales/uk] .co.uk, .ltd.uk, .me.uk, .net.uk, .nic.uk, .org.uk, .plc.uk and .sch.uk are managed by Nominet UK and except for .nic.uk are available for registration by the public (though they all carry various degrees of restrictions).
[src:wales/uk] Other second-level domains are managed by various government agencies, and generally more strongly controlled.
[src:wales/uk] Allocations are on a strict first-come, first-served basis to qualified applicants.
[src:wales/uk] There are no territorial restrictions: applicants need not have any connection to the UK other than those outlined below for .ltd.uk and other restricted domains.
[src:wales/uk] .co.uk is by far the most used of the domains, followed by .org.uk then .me.uk. .plc.uk and .ltd.uk are only rarely used.
[src:wales/uk] The number of new registrations for each of the different .uk domains on a month by month basis can be seen on the Nominet UK website.
[src:wales/uk] The intended restriction of .co.uk to companies is purely nominal; in practice it is open to any and all applicants.
[src:wales/uk] Likewise, whilst .org.uk is for organisations, there are no restrictions on registering domains.
[src:wales/uk] While .me.uk originally had no restrictions on registrants it has since been tightened up to require registrants to be natural persons (i.e. not companies, etc.).
[src:wales/uk] However, registrants in .ltd.uk must be, and remain, private limited companies incorporated under the UK Companies Acts.
[src:wales/uk] In addition, names can only be registered if they correspond (in accordance with the algorithm in the rules of registration) with the exact company name, as recorded at the companies registry at Companies House.
[src:wales/uk] The same conditions apply for public limited companies which wish to use a .plc.uk domain name.
[src:wales/uk] Neither of these domains is widely used.
[src:wales/uk] .net.uk is more open, but the Nominet regulations still mean that a registrant must be an ISP, or a similar body, and that the domain is not used for providing services to end-users. .nic.uk, however, is limited solely to domains operated by Nominet.
[src:wales/uk] .ac.uk domains are intended for the use of higher education institutions and further education colleges, and are also used by some academic support bodies such as the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service public research establishments, and learned societies such as the Royal Society.
[src:wales/uk] Primary and secondary education uses .sch.uk.
[src:wales/uk] Unusually, .sch.uk domains are allocated at the fourth level, with the third level being taken up by the name of the local authority (LA, previously LEA or local education authority) e.g. schoolname.leaname.sch.uk.
[src:wales/uk] For example, the Little Ilford School in Newham has the domain name littleilford.newham.sch.uk and the West Exe School in Exeter, Devon has the domain name westexe.devon.sch.uk.
[src:wales/uk] Previously applications were made in the normal way, but after Nominet came to an arrangement with the education authorities, one domain per school was issued automatically.
[src:wales/uk] Those that had already used another domain were still given one and were able to redirect it to their main domain.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A distinct Welsh culture emerged among the Celtic Britons after the Roman withdrawal from Britain in the 5th century, and Wales was briefly united under Gruffudd ap Llywelyn in 1055.
[src:wales/wales-p01] After over 200 years of war, the conquest of Wales was completed by King Edward I of England in 1283, though Owain Glyndŵr led the Welsh Revolt against English rule in the early 15th century, and briefly re-established an independent Welsh state with its own national parliament (Welsh: *senedd*).
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the 16th century the whole of Wales was annexed by England and incorporated within the English legal system under the Laws in Wales Acts 1535 and 1542.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Distinctive Welsh politics developed in the 19th century.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Welsh Liberalism, exemplified in the late 19th and early 20th century by David Lloyd George, was displaced by the growth of socialism and the Labour Party.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Welsh national feeling grew over the century: a nationalist party, Plaid Cymru, was formed in 1925, and Cymdeithas yr Iaith Gymraeg, the Welsh language society, in 1962.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A governing system of Welsh devolution is employed in Wales, of which the most major step was the formation of the Senedd (Welsh Parliament, formerly the National Assembly for Wales) in 1998, responsible for a range of devolved policy matters.
[src:wales/wales-p01] At the dawn of the Industrial Revolution, development of the mining and metallurgical industries transformed the country from an agricultural society into an industrial one; the South Wales Coalfield's exploitation caused a rapid expansion of Wales's population.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Two-thirds of the population live in South Wales, including Cardiff, Swansea, Newport, and the nearby valleys.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The eastern region of North Wales has about a sixth of the overall population, with Wrexham being the largest northern city.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The remaining parts of Wales are sparsely populated.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Since the decline of the country's traditional extractive and heavy industries, the public sector, light and service industries, and tourism play major roles in its economy.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Agriculture in Wales is largely livestock-based, making Wales a net exporter of animal produce, contributing towards national agricultural self-sufficiency.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Both Welsh and English are official languages.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A majority of the population of Wales speaks English.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Welsh is the dominant language in parts of the north and west, with a total of 538,300 Welsh speakers across the entire country.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales has four UNESCO world heritage sites, of which three are in the north.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The English words *Wales* and *Welsh* derive from the same Old English root (singular *Wealh*, plural *Wēalas*), a descendant of Proto-Germanic **Walhaz*, which was itself derived from the name of the Gauls known to the Romans as *Volcae*.
[src:wales/wales-p01] This term was later used to refer indiscriminately to inhabitants of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Anglo-Saxons came to use the term to refer to the Britons in particular; the plural form *Wēalas* evolved into the name for their territory, Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Historically in Britain, the words were not restricted to modern Wales or to the Welsh but were used to refer to anything that Anglo-Saxons associated with Britons, including other non-Germanic territories in Britain (e.g.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Cornwall) and places in Anglo-Saxon territory associated with Britons (e.g.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Walworth in County Durham and Walton in West Yorkshire).
[src:wales/wales-p01] The modern Welsh name for themselves is *Cymry*, and *Cymru* is the Welsh name for Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] These words (both of which are pronounced [ˈkəm.rɨ]) are descended from the Brythonic word *combrogi*, meaning 'fellow-countrymen', and probably came into use before the 7th century.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In literature, they could be spelt *Kymry* or *Cymry*, regardless of whether it referred to the people or their homeland.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Latinised forms of these names, *Cambrian*, *Cambric* and *Cambria*, survive as names such as the Cambrian Mountains and the Cambrian geological period.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Although the Welsh nation did not arise until the Middle Ages, the territory of Wales was permanently settled from the end of the last ice age onwards.
[src:wales/wales-p01] These first farmers left many impressive funerary monuments, as well as settlement sites that speak to a dispersed culture.
[src:wales/wales-p01] With the arrival of the Bronze Age, the Great Orme in North Wales became Britain's premier producer of copper, one of the key ores for smelting bronze.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It is likely that the wealth of mineral resources in Britain, and especially Wales, attracted the Roman invasion, but by this time the island had become distinctively Celtic in culture, and the Neolithic population was largely replaced.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It was this Iron Age Celtic culture, and their common language, that were called the Britons by the Romans.
[src:wales/wales-p01] With the departure of the Romans, Britain fractured into various kingdoms.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Despite this, there is a sense in which the Roman withdrawal of 383 created a post-Roman nation of Britons, with Magnus Maximus proclaimed Roman emperor in Britannia and Gaul.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Although long before the term *Cymry* (the Welsh term for the Welsh) had been adopted, the concept of a British people, from which the Welsh would emerge, was created here.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Encroachment by Germanic Anglo-Saxon settlers gradually displaced the indigenous culture and language of the Britons, and one group of these Britons became isolated by the geography of the western peninsula, bounded by the sea and English neighbours.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It was these English neighbours who named the land Wallia, and the people Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The people of Wallia, medieval Wales, remained divided into separate kingdoms that fought with each other as much as they fought their English neighbours.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Neither were the communities homogeneously Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Place name, historical records and archaeological evidence point to coastal Viking/Norse settlement in places such as Swansea, Fishguard and Anglesey, and Saxons settled inland amongst the Welsh in places such as Presteigne.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the 10th century, Hywel ap Cadell, later known as Hywel Dda, formed the kingdom of Deheubarth from inheritances in Dyfed and Seisyllwg, and then gained control of the kingdoms of Gwynedd and Powys in 942.
[src:wales/wales-p01] With control of nearly all the territory of Wales, he codified Welsh law, a law code that survived the later fracture of his kingdom, and that became a significant step in the creation of the nation.
[src:wales/wales-p01] With a common culture and an external threat, the kingdoms of Wales began to see themselves as one people.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A century later the Kingdom of Gwynedd was in ascendency, and Gruffydd ap Llywelyn subdued all opposition by 1057, becoming the only king to unite all of Wales, and parts of England on the border.
[src:wales/wales-p01] "Thus, from about 1057 until his death in 1063, the whole of Wales recognised the kingship of Gruffydd ap Llywelyn.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The kingdom did not last, and Gruffydd met his death as a result of a surprise attack by Tostig, brother of the English King, Harold.
[src:wales/wales-p01] After Gruffydd's death, Harold married his widow, but she would be widowed again by the Norman invasion of England in 1066.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Normans followed their invasion of England with incursions into Wales, forming the semi-independent Norman Welsh marches (from the French for borderlands), and dividing them from the unconquered Pura Wallia.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The fortunes of Welsh marcher lords and various Welsh princes ebbed and flowed, until Llywelyn ab Iorwerth (Llywelyn the Great) forced all other Welsh princes to submit to him in 1216.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Yet Wales was divided again after his death, and it was left for his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffudd to secure the supremacy once more, recognised as Prince of Wales by the English king, Henry III, in the treaty of Montgomery of 1267.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Relations with Henry's successor, Edward I, broke down and led to a war of conquest, concluding in 1283 with English victory.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The following year the statute of Rhuddlan ended Welsh independence.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales was divided between principality, ruled by Edward; and the marches, ruled by feudal marcher lords.
[src:wales/wales-p01] This persisted, despite the Welsh rebellion under Owain Glyndŵr of 1400–1415, until the rise of the Tudors, with Welsh support.
[src:wales/wales-p01] With the Laws in Wales Acts of Henry VIII, the Welsh became full citizens in the Kingdom of England, with parliamentary representation.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Welsh border was also formally defined and the territory reunited.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Act of Union 1707 created the Kingdom of Great Britain.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The industrial revolution and the beginning of empire led to the rapid increase in mining and exploitation of Welsh natural materials – metals, coal and slate.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The population of Wales expanded rapidly and Wales moved to the centre of the British economy, but the changes bred resentment, this time towards industrialists and not the English state.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Meanwhile, a series of religious revivals transformed the character of the nation, beginning a tradition of non-conformism.
[src:wales/wales-p01] This carried over into the political sphere too.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The rapid industrialisation of parts of Wales gave rise to strong and radical Welsh working class movements which led to the Merthyr Rising of 1831, the widespread support for Chartism, and the Newport Rising of 1839.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Strong liberal traditions were forged and later replaced by socialism.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Since 1922 Wales has voted Labour in every general election.
[src:wales/wales-p01] From the mid 19th century until 1914, Wales experienced a strengthened political culture, religious and cultural revival, renewed interest in Welsh literature, the revival of Eisteddfodau.
[src:wales/wales-p01] There was a thriving economy, a renewed interest in Welsh language, and music, non-conformist Christianity and the emergence of strong national identity, along with the founding of many national institutions.
[src:wales/wales-p01] However, the period also saw the publication of a report on education that became known as the Treachery of the Blue Books.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The report blamed Welsh language and non-conformism for poor educational standards.
[src:wales/wales-p01] This fed the rise of the Welsh nationalist movement, expressed in the Cymru Fydd movement, which advocated for greater autonomy and recognition of Welsh identity within the United Kingdom.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Calls for devolution grew over the course of a century, and the Government of Wales Act 1998 created a devolved Welsh assembly for the first time, now renamed the Senedd or Welsh Parliament.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales is a generally mountainous country on the western side of central southern Great Britain.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It is about 170 miles (270 km) north to south.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The oft-quoted "size of Wales" is about 20,779 km2 (8,023 sq mi).
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales is bordered by England to the east and by sea in all other directions: the Irish Sea to the north and west, St George's Channel and the Celtic Sea to the southwest and the Bristol Channel to the south.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales has about 1,680 miles (2,700 km) of coastline (along the mean high water mark), including the mainland, Anglesey and Holyhead.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Over 50 islands lie off the Welsh mainland, the largest being Anglesey, in the north-west.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Much of Wales's diverse landscape is mountainous, particularly in the north and central regions.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The mountains were shaped during the last ice age, the Devensian glaciation.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The highest mountains in Wales are in Snowdonia (*Eryri*), of which five are over 1,000 m (3,300 ft).
[src:wales/wales-p01] The highest of these is Snowdon (*Yr Wyddfa*), at 1,085 m (3,560 ft).
[src:wales/wales-p01] The 14 Welsh mountains, or 15 if including Carnedd Gwenllian – often discounted because of its low topographic prominence – over 3,000 feet (910 metres) high are known collectively as the Welsh 3000s and are located in a small area in the north-west.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The highest outside the 3000s is Aran Fawddwy, at 905 metres (2,969 feet), in the south of Snowdonia.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Brecon Beacons (*Bannau Brycheiniog*) are in the south (highest point Pen y Fan, at 886 metres (2,907 feet)), and are joined by the Cambrian Mountains in Mid Wales (highest point Pumlumon, at 752 metres (2,467 feet)).
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales has three national parks: Snowdonia, Brecon Beacons, and Pembrokeshire Coast (*Arfordir Penfro*).
[src:wales/wales-p01] It has five Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty: Anglesey, the Clwydian Range and Dee Valley, the Gower Peninsula, the Llŷn Peninsula, and the Wye Valley.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Gower Peninsula was the first area in the United Kingdom to be designated as an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, in 1956.
[src:wales/wales-p01] As of 2019, the coastline of Wales had 40 Blue Flag beaches, three Blue Flag marinas and one Blue Flag boat operator.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The south and west coasts of Wales, along with the Irish and Cornish coasts, are frequently blasted by Atlantic westerlies/south-westerlies that, over the years, have sunk and wrecked many vessels.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 1859 over 110 ships were destroyed off the coast of Wales in a hurricane that saw more than 800 lives lost across Britain.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The greatest single loss occurred with the sinking of the *Royal Charter* off Anglesey in which 459 people died.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The 19th century saw over 100 vessels lost with an average loss of 78 sailors per year.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wartime action caused losses near Holyhead, Milford Haven and Swansea.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Because of offshore rocks and unlit islands, Anglesey and Pembrokeshire are still notorious for shipwrecks, most notably the *Sea Empress* oil spill in 1996.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The first border between Wales and England was zonal, apart from around the River Wye, which was the first accepted boundary.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Offa's Dyke was supposed to form an early distinct line, but this was thwarted by Gruffudd ap Llewellyn, who reclaimed swathes of land beyond the dyke.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Act of Union 1536 formed a linear border stretching from the mouth of the Dee to the mouth of the Wye.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Even after the Act of Union, many of the borders remained vague and moveable until the Sunday Closing (Wales) Act 1881, which forced local businesses to decide which country they fell within to accept either the Welsh or English law.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The earliest geological period of the Palaeozoic era, the Cambrian, takes its name from the Cambrian Mountains, where geologists first identified Cambrian remnants.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the mid-19th century, Roderick Murchison and Adam Sedgwick used their studies of Welsh geology to establish certain principles of stratigraphy and palaeontology.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The next two periods of the Palaeozoic era, the Ordovician and Silurian, were named after ancient Celtic tribes from this area.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales lies within the north temperate zone.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It has a changeable, maritime climate and is one of the wettest countries in Europe.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Welsh weather is often cloudy, wet and windy, with warm summers and mild winters.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales's wildlife is typical of Britain with several distinctions.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Because of its long coastline, Wales hosts a variety of seabirds.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The coasts and surrounding islands are home to colonies of gannets, Manx shearwater, puffins, kittiwakes, shags and razorbills.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In comparison, with 60 per cent of Wales above the 150m contour, the country also supports a variety of upland-habitat birds, including raven and ring ouzel.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Birds of prey include the merlin, hen harrier and the red kite, a national symbol of Welsh wildlife.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In total, more than 200 different species of bird have been seen at the RSPB reserve at Conwy, including seasonal visitors.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Larger mammals, including brown bears, wolves and wildcats, died out during the Norman period.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Today, mammals include shrews, voles, badgers, otters, stoats, weasels, hedgehogs and fifteen species of bat.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Two species of small rodent, the yellow-necked mouse and the dormouse, are of special Welsh note being found at the historically undisturbed border area.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The pine marten, which has been sighted occasionally, has been reintroduced in parts of Wales since 2015, having previously not been officially recorded since the 1950s.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The polecat was nearly driven to extinction in Britain, but hung on in Wales and is now rapidly spreading.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In March 2021, Natural Resources Wales (NRW) granted a licence to release up to six beavers in the Dyfi Valley, the first official beaver release in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Believed to be home to some of Wales's rarest land invertebrates, some 2,500 disused coal tips are the subject of study by the Welsh Government; the tips are home to a wide variety of other wildlife.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The waters of south-west Wales of Gower, Pembrokeshire, and Cardigan Bay attract marine animals, including basking sharks, Atlantic grey seals, leatherback turtles, dolphins, porpoises, jellyfish, crabs and lobsters.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Pembrokeshire and Ceredigion, in particular, are recognised as an area of international importance for bottlenose dolphins, and New Quay has the only summer residence of bottlenose dolphins in the whole of the UK.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Freshwater fish of note include char, eel, salmon, shad, sparling and Arctic char, while the gwyniad is unique to Wales, found only in Llyn Tegid (Bala Lake).
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales is known for its shellfish, including cockles, limpet, mussels and periwinkles.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Herring, mackerel and hake are the more common of the country's marine fish.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The north facing high grounds of Snowdonia support a relict pre-glacial flora including the iconic Snowdon lily – *Gagea serotina* – and other alpine species such as *Saxifraga cespitosa*, *Saxifraga oppositifolia* and *Silene acaulis*.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales has a number of plant species not found elsewhere in the UK, including the spotted rock-rose *Tuberaria guttata* on Anglesey and *Draba aizoides* on the Gower.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales is a country that is part of the sovereign state of the United Kingdom.
[src:wales/wales-p01] ISO 3166-2:GB formerly defined Wales as a principality, with England and Scotland defined as countries and Northern Ireland as a province.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the House of Commons – the 650-member lower house of the UK Parliament – there are 32 members of Parliament (MPs) who represent Welsh constituencies.
[src:wales/wales-p01] At the 2024 general election, 27 Labour and Labour Co-op MPs were elected, along with 4 Plaid Cymru MPs and 1 Liberal Democrat MP from Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Wales Office is a department of the UK government responsible for Wales, whose minister, the Secretary of State for Wales (Welsh secretary), sits in the UK cabinet.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales has a devolved, unicameral legislature known as the Senedd (Senedd Cymru – Welsh Parliament) which holds devolved powers from the UK Parliament via a reserved powers model.
[src:wales/wales-p01] For the purposes of local government, Wales has been divided into 22 council areas since 1996.
[src:wales/wales-p01] These "principal areas" are responsible for the provision of all local government services.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Following devolution in 1997, the Government of Wales Act 1998 created a Welsh devolved assembly, the National Assembly for Wales, with the power to determine how Wales's central government budget is spent and administered.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Eight years later, the Government of Wales Act 2006 reformed the National Assembly for Wales and allowed further powers to be granted to it more easily.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Act also created a system of government with a separate executive, the Welsh Government, drawn from and accountable to the legislature, the National Assembly.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Following a successful referendum in 2011, the National Assembly was empowered to make laws, known as Acts of the Assembly, on all matters in devolved subject areas, without requiring the UK Parliament's approval of legislative competence.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In May 2020, the National Assembly was renamed "Senedd Cymru" or "the Welsh Parliament", commonly known as the Senedd in both English and Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Devolved areas of responsibility include agriculture, economic development, education, health, housing, local government, social services, tourism, transport and the Welsh language.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Welsh Government also promotes Welsh interests abroad.
[src:wales/wales-p01] By tradition, Welsh Law was compiled during an assembly held at Whitland around 930 by Hywel Dda (*Hywel the Good*), king of most of Wales between 942 and his death in 950.
[src:wales/wales-p01] *Cyfraith Hywel* (Welsh for 'law of Hywel Dda') codified the previously existing folk laws and legal customs that had evolved in Wales over centuries.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Welsh Law emphasised the payment of compensation for a crime to the victim, or the victim's kin, rather than punishment by the ruler.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Other than in the Marches, where March law was imposed by the Marcher Lords, Welsh Law remained in force only for civil cases after the Statute of Rhuddlan in 1284.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Edward I of England annexed the Principality of Wales following the death of Llywelyn ap Gruffudd, and Welsh Law was replaced for criminal cases under the Statute.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Marcher Law and Welsh Law remained in force until Henry VIII of England annexed the whole of Wales under the Laws in Wales Acts 1535 and 1542 (often referred to as the Acts of Union of 1536 and 1543), after which English law applied to the whole of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Wales and Berwick Act 1746 provided that all laws that applied to England would automatically apply to Wales (and the Anglo-Scottish border town of Berwick) unless the law explicitly stated otherwise; this Act was repealed with regard to Wales by the Welsh Language Act 1967.
[src:wales/wales-p01] English law has been the legal system of England and Wales since 1536.
[src:wales/wales-p01] English law is regarded as a common law system, with no major codification of the law and legal precedents are binding as opposed to persuasive.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The court system is headed by the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom which is the highest court of appeal in the land for criminal and civil cases.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Senior Courts of England and Wales is the highest court of first instance as well as an appellate court.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The three divisions are the Court of Appeal, the High Court of Justice, and the Crown Court.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Minor cases are heard by magistrates' courts or the County Court.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2007 the Wales and Cheshire Region (known as the Wales and Cheshire Circuit before 2005) came to an end when Cheshire was attached to the North-Western England Region.
[src:wales/wales-p01] From that point, Wales became a legal unit in its own right, although it remains part of the single jurisdiction of England and Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Senedd has the authority to draft and approve laws outside of the UK Parliamentary system to meet the specific needs of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Through this primary legislation, the Welsh Government can then also enact more specific subordinate legislation.
[src:wales/wales-p01] There have however been some actions by the UK Government which has undermined devolved powers of the Welsh Government such as with the United Kingdom Internal Market Act 2020 and Pride in Place scheme 2025.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales is served by four regional police forces: Dyfed-Powys Police, Gwent Police, North Wales Police, and South Wales Police.
[src:wales/wales-p01] There are five prisons in Wales: four in the southern half of the country, and one in Wrexham.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales has no women's prisons: female inmates are imprisoned in England.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Over the last 250 years, Wales has been transformed from an agricultural country to an industrial, and then to a post-industrial economy.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the 1950s, Wales's GDP was twice as big as Ireland's; by the 2020s, Ireland's economy was four times that of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Since the Second World War, the service sector has come to account for the majority of jobs, a feature typifying most advanced economies. in 2018, according to OECD and Eurostat data, gross domestic product (GDP) in Wales was £75 billion, an increase of 3.3 per cent from 2017.
[src:wales/wales-p01] GDP per head in Wales in 2018 was £23,866, an increase of 2.9 per cent on 2017.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the three months to December 2017, 72.7 per cent of working-age adults were employed, compared to 75.2 per cent across the UK as a whole.
[src:wales/wales-p01] For the 2018–19 fiscal year, the Welsh fiscal deficit accounts for 19.4 per cent of Wales's estimated GDP.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2019, Wales was a net exporter of electricity.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It produced 27.9 TWh of electricity while only consuming 14.7 TWh.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2021, the Welsh government said that more than half the country's energy needs were being met by renewable sources, 2 per cent of which was from 363 hydropower projects.
[src:wales/wales-p01] By UK law, Wales contributes to items that do not directly benefit Wales e.g. over £5 billion for HS2 "which will damage the Welsh economy by £200m pa", according to the UK and Welsh Government's transport adviser Mark Barry.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales also pays more in military costs than most similar-sized countries e.g.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales pays twice the amount Ireland spends on the military.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The UK government spends £1.75bn per year on the military in Wales, which is almost as much as Wales spends on education every year (£1.8 billion in 2018/19) and five times as much as the total amount spent on the police in Wales (£365 million).
[src:wales/wales-p01] From the middle of the 19th century until the post-war era, the mining and export of coal was the dominant industry.
[src:wales/wales-p01] At its peak of production in 1913, nearly 233,000 men and women were employed in the South Wales coalfield, mining 56 million tons of coal.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Cardiff was once the largest coal-exporting port in the world and, for a few years before the First World War, handled a greater tonnage of cargo than either London or Liverpool.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the 1920s, over 40 per cent of the male Welsh population worked in heavy industry.
[src:wales/wales-p01] According to Phil Williams, the Great Depression "devastated Wales", north and south, because of its "overwhelming dependence on coal and steel".
[src:wales/wales-p01] From the mid-1970s, the Welsh economy faced massive restructuring with large numbers of jobs in heavy industry disappearing and being replaced eventually by new ones in light industry and in services.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, Wales was successful in attracting an above average share of foreign direct investment in the UK.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Much of the new industry was essentially of a "branch (or "screwdriver") factory" type where a manufacturing plant or call centre is in Wales but the most highly-paid jobs in the company are elsewhere.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Poor-quality soil in much of Wales is unsuitable for crop-growing, so livestock farming has been the focus of farming.
[src:wales/wales-p01] About 78 per cent of the land surface is used for agriculture.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Welsh landscape, with its three national parks and Blue Flag beaches, attracts large numbers of tourists, who bolster the economy of rural areas.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales, like Northern Ireland, has relatively few high value-added employment in sectors such as finance and research and development, attributable in part to a comparative lack of "economic mass" (i.e. population) – Wales lacks a large metropolitan centre.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The lack of high value-added employment is reflected in lower economic output per head relative to other regions of the UK: in 2002 it stood at 90 per cent of the EU25 average and around 80 per cent of the UK average.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In June 2008, Wales made history by becoming the first nation to be awarded Fairtrade status.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The pound sterling is the currency used in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Numerous Welsh banks issued their own banknotes in the 19th century: the last bank to do so closed in 1908.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Since then the Bank of England has had a monopoly on the issue of banknotes in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Commercial Bank of Wales, established in Cardiff by Sir Julian Hodge in 1971, was taken over by the Bank of Scotland in 1988 and absorbed into its parent company in 2002.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Royal Mint, which issues the coinage circulating through the whole of the UK, has been based at a single site in Llantrisant since 1980.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Since decimalisation, in 1971, at least one of the coins in circulation emphasises Wales such as the 1995 and 2000 one pound coin.
[src:wales/wales-p01] As at 2012, the last designs devoted to Wales saw production in 2008.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Rail transport in Wales includes the Wales & Borders franchise, which is overseen by the Welsh Government with most passenger services operated by Transport for Wales Rail.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Cardiff region has its own urban rail network.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Beeching cuts in the 1960s mean that most of the remaining network is geared toward east–west travel connecting with the Irish Sea ports for ferries to Ireland.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Trains in Wales are mainly diesel-powered but the South Wales Main Line branch of the Great Western Main Line used by services from London Paddington to Cardiff has undergone electrification, although the programme experienced significant delays and cost overruns.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Many of the Valley Lines are also undergoing electrification, under the South Wales Metro project.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A North-South railway has been suggested to better link North and South Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Cardiff Airport is the international airport of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Providing links to European, African and Asian destinations, it is about 12 miles (19 km) southwest of Cardiff city centre, in the Vale of Glamorgan.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Intra-Wales flights used to run between Anglesey (Valley) and Cardiff, and were operated since 2017 by Eastern Airways; as of 2022, those flights are no longer available.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Other internal flights operate to northern England, Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Regular ferry services to Ireland operate from Holyhead, Pembroke Dock and Fishguard.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Swansea to Cork service was cancelled in 2006, reinstated in March 2010, and withdrawn again in 2012.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Most of the increase came in the coal mining districts, especially Glamorganshire, which grew from 71,000 in 1801 to 232,000 in 1851 and 1,122,000 in 1911.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Part of this increase can be attributed to the demographic transition seen in most industrialising countries during the Industrial Revolution, as death rates dropped and birth rates remained steady.
[src:wales/wales-p01] However, there was also large-scale immigration into Wales during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The English were the most numerous group, but there were also considerable numbers of Irish and smaller numbers of other ethnic groups, including Italians, who migrated to South Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales also received immigration from various parts of the British Commonwealth of Nations in the 20th century, and African-Caribbean and Asian communities add to the ethnocultural mix, particularly in urban Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Many of these now self-identify as Welsh, and distinctions between 19th and 20th century immigrants are not viewed as significant.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The population in 1972 stood at 2.74 million and remained broadly static for the rest of the decade.
[src:wales/wales-p01] However, in the early 1980s, the population fell due to net emigration out of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Since the 1980s, net migration has generally been inward, and has contributed more to population growth than natural change.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The resident population of Wales in 2021 according to the census was 3,107,500 (1,586,600 female and 1,521,000 male), an increase of 1.4 per cent over 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A decreased change from the 5 per cent increase between 2001 and 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales accounted for 5.2 per cent of the population of England and Wales in 2021.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Wales has seven cities: Cardiff, Newport, Swansea, Wrexham, Bangor, St Asaph and St Davids.
[src:wales/wales-p01] (The last two of these have city status in the United Kingdom despite their small populations.) Wrexham, north Wales's largest settlement, became Wales's newest and seventh city in September 2022.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The 2021 census showed that 93.8 per cent of the population of Wales identified as "White", compared to 95.6 per cent in 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] 90.6 per cent of the population identified as "White: Welsh, English, Scottish, Northern Irish or British" in 2021.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The second-highest ethnicity in 2021 was "Asian, Asian Welsh or Asian British" at 2.9 per cent of the population, compared to 2.3 per cent in 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The local authorities with the highest proportions of "high-level" ethnic groups other than "White" were mainly urban areas including Cardiff, Newport and Swansea.
[src:wales/wales-p01] 5.3 per cent of households in Wales were multiple ethnic group households, up from 4.2 per cent in 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2021, the first statue of a named, non-fictional woman outdoors was raised for Wales's first black headteacher, Betty Campbell.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2023, Patti Flynn (a contemporary of Shirley Bassey, both of Tiger Bay, Cardiff) became the first black Welsh woman to be awarded a purple plaque.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2024, Vaughan Gething was elected First Minister of Wales becoming the first black head of government in Europe; he had previously served as Secretary for Finance.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The 2021 census showed that only 55.2 per cent identified as "Welsh only" down from 57.5% in 2011, and 8.1 per cent identified as "Welsh and British" up from 7.1%, giving the combined proportion of only 63.3 per cent (down from 64.4) of people identifying as Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p01] 18.5% identified as "British only", and 9.1% identified as "English only", meaning 18.2% of people living in Wales identified with another nationality, with 5.4% being a non-UK identity, the largest being Polish at 0.7% overall.
[src:wales/wales-p01] There is a geographical distribution of identities, with the highest amount of "Welsh only" identities being in the South Wales Valleys and West Wales, with Merthyr Tydfil county recording the single highest rate of 70%.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Meanwhile English and British identity is highest among areas near the English border and coastal communities, with Flintshire recording the lowest amount of "Welsh only" identities at 34.7%.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Urban areas are also more diverse with Cardiff recording the most number of different national identities.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Welsh Annual Population Survey showed that the proportion of people who identified as Welsh versus another identity was 62.3 per cent in 2022, compared to 69.2 per cent in 2001.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Welsh is an official language in Wales as legislated by the Welsh Language (Wales) Measure 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Both Welsh and English are also official languages of the Senedd.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The proportion of the Welsh population able to speak the Welsh language fell from just under 50 per cent in 1901 to 43.5 per cent in 1911, and continued to fall to 18.9 per cent in 1981.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The results of the 2001 Census showed an increase in the number of Welsh speakers to 21 per cent of the population aged 3 and older, compared with 18.7 per cent in 1991 and 19 per cent in 1981.
[src:wales/wales-p01] This compares with a pattern of steady decline indicated by census results during the 20th century.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the 2011 census it was recorded that the proportion of people able to speak Welsh had dropped from 20.8 per cent to 19 per cent (still higher than 1991).
[src:wales/wales-p01] Despite an increase in the overall size of the Welsh population this still meant that the number of Welsh speakers in Wales dropped from 582,000 in 2001 to 562,000 in 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] However, this figure was still higher than the 508,000 people (or 18.7 per cent of the population) who said they could speak Welsh in the 1991 census.
[src:wales/wales-p01] According to the 2021 census, the Welsh-speaking population of Wales aged three or older was 17.8 per cent (538,300 people) and nearly three-quarters of the population in Wales said they had no Welsh language skills.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Other estimates suggest that 29.7 per cent (899,500) of people aged three or older in Wales could speak Welsh in June 2022.
[src:wales/wales-p01] English is spoken by almost all people in Wales and is the main language in most of the country.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Code-switching is common in all parts of Wales and is known by various terms, though none is recognised by professional linguists.
[src:wales/wales-p01] "Wenglish" is the Welsh dialect of the English language.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It has been influenced significantly by Welsh grammar and includes words derived from Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Northern and western Wales retain many areas where Welsh is spoken as a first language by the majority of the population, and English learnt as a second language.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Although monoglotism in young children continues, life-long monoglotism in Welsh no longer occurs.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Since Poland joined the European Union, Wales has seen a significant increase in Polish immigrants.
[src:wales/wales-p01] This has made Polish the most common main language in Wales after English and Welsh, at 0.7 per cent of the population.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Forms of Christianity have dominated religious life in what is now Wales for more than 1,400 years.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The 2021 census recorded that 46.5 per cent had "No religion", more than any single religious affiliation and up from 32.1 per cent in 2011.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The largest religion in Wales is Christianity, with 43.6 per cent of the population describing themselves as Christian in the 2021 census.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The patron saint of Wales is Saint David (*Dewi Sant*), with Saint David's Day (*Dydd Gŵyl Dewi Sant*) celebrated annually on 1 March.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The early 20th century saw a religious revival, the 1904–1905 Welsh Revival, which started through the evangelism of Evan Roberts and brought large numbers of converts, sometimes whole communities, to non-Anglican Christianity.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Church in Wales with 56,000 adherents has the largest attendance of the denominations.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It is a province of the Anglican Communion, and was part of the Church of England until disestablishment in 1920 under the Welsh Church Act 1914.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The first Independent Church in Wales was founded at Llanvaches in 1638 by William Wroth.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Presbyterian Church of Wales was born out of the Welsh Methodist revival in the 18th century and seceded from the Church of England in 1811.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The second largest attending faith in Wales is Roman Catholic, with an estimated 43,000 adherents.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Non-Christian religions are small in Wales, making up approximately 2.7 per cent of the population.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Islam is the largest, with 24,000 (0.8 per cent) reported Muslims in the 2011 census.
[src:wales/wales-p01] There are also communities of Hindus and Sikhs, mainly in the south Wales cities of Newport, Cardiff and Swansea, while the largest concentration of Buddhists is in the western rural county of Ceredigion.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Judaism was the first non-Christian faith to be established in Wales since Roman times, though by 2001 the community had declined to approximately 2,000 and as of 2019 only numbers in the hundreds.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A distinct education system has developed in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Formal education before the 18th century was the preserve of the elite.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The first grammar schools were established in Welsh towns such as Ruthin, Brecon and Cowbridge.
[src:wales/wales-p01] One of the first successful schooling systems was started by Griffith Jones, who introduced the circulating schools in the 1730s; these are believed to have taught half the country's population to read.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In the early 19th century, English became the usual language of instruction at schools in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] While the country's working class was largely Welsh-speaking at the time, Welsh public opinion wished for children to learn English.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Many schools used corporal punishment to stop children from speaking Welsh in the first half of the 19th century; the practice declined in the second half of the century.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The British government never prohibited the use of Welsh at schools but it treated English as the assumed language of instruction.
[src:wales/wales-p01] More Welsh was gradually used at schools in Welsh-speaking areas in the mid to late 19th century and teaching of the language began to receive moderate government support from the late 19th century.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The University College of Wales opened in Aberystwyth in 1872.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Cardiff and Bangor followed, and the three colleges came together in 1893 to form the University of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Welsh Intermediate Education Act 1889 created 95 secondary schools.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The Welsh Department for the Board of Education followed in 1907, which gave Wales its first significant educational devolution.
[src:wales/wales-p01] A resurgence in Welsh-language schools in the latter half of the 20th century at nursery and primary level saw attitudes shift towards teaching in the medium of Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Welsh is a compulsory subject in all of Wales's state schools for pupils aged 5–16 years old.
[src:wales/wales-p01] While there has never been an exclusively Welsh-language college, Welsh-medium higher education is delivered through the individual universities and has since 2011 been supported by the Coleg Cymraeg Cenedlaethol (Welsh-language National College) as a delocalised federal institution.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2021–2022, there were 1,470 maintained schools in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2021–22, the country had 471,131 pupils taught by 25,210 full-time equivalent teachers.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Public healthcare in Wales is provided by NHS Wales (*GIG Cymru*), through seven local health boards and three all-Wales trusts.
[src:wales/wales-p01] It was originally formed as part of the NHS structure for England and Wales by the National Health Service Act 1946, but with powers over the NHS in Wales coming under the Secretary of State for Wales in 1969.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Responsibility for NHS Wales passed to the Welsh Assembly under devolution in 1999, and is now the responsibility of the Minister for Health and Social Services.
[src:wales/wales-p01] Historically, Wales was served by smaller 'cottage' hospitals, built as voluntary institutions.
[src:wales/wales-p01] As newer, more expensive, diagnostic techniques and treatments became available, clinical work has been concentrated in newer, larger district hospitals.
[src:wales/wales-p01] In 2006, there were seventeen district hospitals in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p01] NHS Wales directly employs over 90,000 staff, making it Wales's biggest employer.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The National Survey for Wales in 2021–22 reported that 72 per cent of adults surveyed had good or very good general health, 19 per cent had fair general health and 8 had bad or very bad general health.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The survey recorded that 46 per cent of Welsh adults had a long-standing illness, such as arthritis, asthma, diabetes or heart disease.
[src:wales/wales-p01] The survey also reported that 13 per cent of the adult population were smokers, 16 per cent admitted drinking alcohol above weekly recommended guidelines, while 56 per cent undertook the recommended 150 minutes of physical activity each week.
[src:wales/wales-p01] According to the survey, 30 per cent of adults in Wales reported to have eaten at least 5 portions of fruit or vegetables the previous day and 36 per cent reported a healthy weight.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales has a distinctive culture including its own language, customs, holidays and music.
[src:wales/wales-p02] There are four UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Wales: The Castles and Town Walls of King Edward I in Gwynedd; Pontcysyllte Aqueduct and Canal; the Blaenavon Industrial Landscape; and The Slate Landscape of Northwest Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Amgueddfa Cymru – Museum Wales was founded by royal charter in 1907 as the National Museum of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] It operates at seven sites: National Museum Cardiff, St Fagans National History Museum, Big Pit National Coal Museum, National Wool Museum, National Slate Museum, National Roman Legion Museum, and the National Waterfront Museum.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The National Library of Wales, based in Aberystwyth, houses important collections of printed works, including the Sir John Williams Collection and the Shirburn Castle collection, as well as art collections including portraits and photographs, ephemera and Ordnance Survey maps.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Remnants of native Celtic mythology of the pre-Christian Britons was passed down orally by the *cynfeirdd* (the early poets).
[src:wales/wales-p02] Some of their work survives in later medieval Welsh manuscripts: the Black Book of Carmarthen and the Book of Aneirin (both 13th-century); the Book of Taliesin and the White Book of Rhydderch (both 14th-century); and the Red Book of Hergest (c.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The prose stories from the White and Red Books are known as the *Mabinogion*.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Poems such as *Cad Goddeu* (The Battle of the Trees) and mnemonic list-texts like the *Welsh Triads* and the *Thirteen Treasures of the Island of Britain*, also contain mythological material.
[src:wales/wales-p02] These texts include the earliest forms of the Arthurian legend and the traditional history of post-Roman Britain.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales has one of the oldest unbroken literary traditions in Europe going back to the sixth century and including Geoffrey of Monmouth and Gerald of Wales, regarded as among the finest Latin authors of the Middle Ages.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The earliest body of Welsh verse, by poets Taliesin and Aneirin, survive not in their original form, but in much-changed, medieval versions.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Welsh poetry and native lore and learning survived through the era of the Poets of the Princes (c.
[src:wales/wales-p02] 1100–1280) and then the Poets of the Gentry (c.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The former were professional poets who composed eulogies and elegies to their patrons while the latter favoured the cywydd metre.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The period produced one of Wales's greatest poets, Dafydd ap Gwilym.
[src:wales/wales-p02] After the Anglicisation of the gentry the tradition declined.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Despite the extinction of the professional poet, the integration of the native elite into a wider cultural world did bring other literary benefits.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Renaissance scholars such as William Salesbury and John Davies brought humanist ideals from English universities.
[src:wales/wales-p02] In 1588 William Morgan became the first person to translate the Bible into Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p02] From the 16th century the proliferation of the 'free-metre' verse became the most important development in Welsh poetry, but from the middle of the 17th century a host of imported accentual metres from England became very popular.
[src:wales/wales-p02] By the 19th century the creation of a Welsh epic, fuelled by the eisteddfod, became an obsession with Welsh-language writers.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The output of this period was prolific in quantity but unequal in quality.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Initially excluded, religious denominations came to dominate the competitions, with bardic themes becoming scriptural and didactic.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Developments in 19th-century Welsh literature include Lady Charlotte Guest's translation into English of the Mabinogion, one of the most important medieval Welsh prose works of Celtic mythology.
[src:wales/wales-p02] 1885 saw the publication of *Rhys Lewis* by Daniel Owen, credited as the first novel written in the Welsh language.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The 20th century saw a move from the verbose Victorian Welsh style, with works such as Thomas Gwynn Jones's *Ymadawiad Arthur*.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The First World War had a profound effect on Welsh literature with a more pessimistic style championed by T.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The industrialisation of south Wales saw a further shift with the likes of Rhydwen Williams who used the poetry and metre of a bygone rural Wales but in the context of an industrial landscape.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The inter-war period is dominated by Saunders Lewis, for his political and reactionary views as much as his plays, poetry and criticism.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The careers of some 1930s writers continued after World War Two, including those of Gwyn Thomas, Vernon Watkins, and Dylan Thomas, whose most famous work *Under Milk Wood* was first broadcast in 1954.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Thomas was one of the most notable and popular Welsh writers of the 20th century and one of the most innovative poets of his time.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The attitude of the post-war generation of Welsh writers in English towards Wales differs from the previous generation, with greater sympathy for Welsh nationalism and the Welsh language.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The change is linked to the nationalism of Saunders Lewis and the burning of the Bombing School on the Llŷn Peninsula in 1936.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Thomas (1913–2000) was the most important figure throughout the second half of the 20th century.
[src:wales/wales-p02] He "did not learn the Welsh language until he was 30 and wrote all his poems in English".
[src:wales/wales-p02] Major writers in the second half of the 20th century include Emyr Humphreys (1919–2020), who during his long writing career published over twenty novels, and Raymond Williams (1921–1988).
[src:wales/wales-p02] Works of Celtic art have been found in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] In the Early Medieval period, the Celtic Christianity of Wales was part of the Insular art of the British Isles.
[src:wales/wales-p02] A number of illuminated manuscripts from Wales survive, including the 8th-century Hereford Gospels and Lichfield Gospels.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The 11th-century Ricemarch Psalter (now in Dublin) is certainly Welsh, made in St David's, and shows a late Insular style with unusual Viking influence.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Some Welsh artists of the 16th–18th centuries tended to leave the country to work, moving to London or Italy.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Richard Wilson (1714–1782) is arguably the first major British landscapist; although more notable for his Italian scenes, he painted several Welsh scenes on visits from London.
[src:wales/wales-p02] By the late 18th century, the popularity of landscape art grew and clients were found in the larger Welsh towns, allowing more Welsh artists to stay in their homeland.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Artists from outside Wales were also drawn to paint Welsh scenery, at first because of the Celtic Revival.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Industrial Schools Act 1857 provided for the establishment of a number of art schools throughout the United Kingdom, and the Cardiff School of Art opened in 1865.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Graduates still very often had to leave Wales to work, but Betws-y-Coed became a popular centre for artists, and its artists' colony helped to form the Royal Cambrian Academy of Art in 1881.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The sculptor Sir William Goscombe John made works for Welsh commissions, although he had settled in London.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Christopher Williams, whose subjects were mostly resolutely Welsh, was also based in London.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Stephens and Andrew Vicari had very successful careers as portraitists, based respectively in the United States and France.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Welsh painters gravitated towards the art capitals of Europe.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Augustus John and his sister Gwen John lived mostly in London and Paris.
[src:wales/wales-p02] However, the landscapists Sir Kyffin Williams and Peter Prendergast lived in Wales for most of their lives, while remaining in touch with the wider art world.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Ceri Richards was very engaged in the Welsh art scene as a teacher in Cardiff and even after moving to London; he was a figurative painter in international styles including Surrealism.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Various artists have moved to Wales, including Eric Gill, the London-Welshman David Jones, and the sculptor Jonah Jones.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Kardomah Gang was an intellectual circle in Swansea, centred on the poet Dylan Thomas and the poet and artist Vernon Watkins, which also included the painter Alfred Janes.
[src:wales/wales-p02] South Wales had several notable potteries, one of the first important sites being the Ewenny Pottery in Bridgend, which began producing earthenware in the 17th century.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Portmeirion Pottery, founded in 1960 by Susan Williams-Ellis (daughter of Clough Williams-Ellis, creator of the Italianate village of Portmeirion, Gwynedd) is based in Stoke-on-Trent, England.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales became the UK's first digital television nation in 2010.
[src:wales/wales-p02] BBC Cymru Wales is the national broadcaster, producing both television and radio programmes in Welsh and English.
[src:wales/wales-p02] It has also produced programmes such as *Life on Mars*, *Doctor Who* and *Torchwood* for BBC's network audience across the United Kingdom.
[src:wales/wales-p02] ITV, the UK's main commercial broadcaster, has a Welsh-orientated service branded ITV Cymru Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Its output was mostly in Welsh at peak hours, but shared English-language content with Channel 4 at other times.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Since the digital switchover the channel has broadcast exclusively in Welsh.
[src:wales/wales-p02] BBC Radio Cymru is the BBC's Welsh-language radio service, which broadcasts throughout Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] A number of independent radio stations broadcast in the Welsh regions, predominantly in English.
[src:wales/wales-p02] In 2006, several regional radio stations broadcast in Welsh: output ranged from two two-minute news bulletins each weekday (Radio Maldwyn) to over 14 hours of Welsh-language programmes weekly (Swansea Sound) to essentially bilingual stations such as Heart Cymru and Radio Ceredigion.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Most of the newspapers sold and read in Wales are national newspapers available throughout Britain.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The *Western Mail* is Wales's only print national daily newspaper.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales-based regional daily newspapers include the *Daily Post* (which covers North Wales), the *South Wales Evening Post* (Swansea), the *South Wales Echo* (Cardiff), and the *South Wales Argus* (Newport).
[src:wales/wales-p02] *Y Cymro* is a Welsh-language newspaper, published weekly.
[src:wales/wales-p02] *Wales on Sunday* is the only Welsh Sunday newspaper that covers the whole of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Books Council of Wales is the Welsh-Government-funded body tasked with promoting Welsh literature in Welsh and English.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The BCW provides publishing grants for qualifying English- and Welsh-language publications.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Around 650 books are published each year, by some of the dozens of Welsh publishers.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales's main publishing houses include Gomer Press, Gwasg Carreg Gwalch, Honno, the University of Wales Press and Y Lolfa.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Journals with a Welsh focus include *Cambria* (a Welsh affairs magazine published bi-monthly in English), *Planet*, and *Poetry Wales*.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Welsh-language magazines include the current affairs titles *Golwg* ("View"), published weekly, and *Barn* ("Opinion"), published monthly.
[src:wales/wales-p02] *Y Wawr* ("The Dawn") is published quarterly by *Merched y Wawr*, the national organisation for women.
[src:wales/wales-p02] *Y Traethodydd* ("The Essayist"), a quarterly publication by the Presbyterian Church of Wales, first appeared in 1845 and is the oldest Welsh publication still in print.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales, "the land of song", is notable for its solo artists, its male voice choirs and its harpists.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The annual *National Eisteddfod* is the country's main performance festival.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The *Llangollen International Eisteddfod* provides an opportunity for the singers and musicians of the world to perform.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Welsh Folk Song Society publishes collections of historical songs and tunes.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Traditional instruments of Wales include the *telyn deires* (triple harp), fiddle, *crwth* (bowed lyre) and the *pibgorn* (hornpipe).
[src:wales/wales-p02] Male voice choirs emerged in the 19th century, formed as the tenor and bass sections of chapel choirs, and embraced the popular secular hymns of the day.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Welsh congregations and choirs were known for singing in a rousing four-voice style, becoming characteristic of the country.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Many of the historic choirs survive in modern Wales, singing a mixture of traditional and popular songs.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The BBC National Orchestra of Wales performs in Wales and internationally.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Welsh National Opera is based at the Wales Millennium Centre in Cardiff Bay, while the National Youth Orchestra of Wales was the first of its type in the world.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales has a tradition of producing notable singers in both the classical and pop arenas, as well as some popular bands.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Welsh folk music scene has enjoyed a resurgence in the 21st century.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The earliest surviving Welsh plays are two medieval miracle plays, *Y Tri Brenin o Gwlen* ("The three Kings from Cologne") and *Y Dioddefaint a'r Atgyfodiad* ("The Passion and the Resurrection").
[src:wales/wales-p02] A recognised Welsh tradition of theatre emerged during the 18th century, in the form of an interlude, a metrical play performed at fairs and markets.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Drama in the early 20th century thrived, but the country established neither a Welsh National Theatre nor a national ballet company.
[src:wales/wales-p02] After the Second World War, the substantial number of amateur theatre companies reduced by two-thirds.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Competition from television in the mid-20th century led to greater professionalism in the theatre.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Plays by Emlyn Williams and Alun Owen and others were staged, while Welsh actors, including Richard Burton and Anthony Hopkins, were establishing international reputations.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales has also produced some well-known comedians.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Traditional dances include Welsh folk dancing and clog dancing.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The first mention of dancing in Wales is in a 12th-century account by Giraldus Cambrensis, but by the 19th century traditional dance had all but died out due to religious opposition.
[src:wales/wales-p02] In the 20th century a revival was led by Lois Blake (1890–1974).
[src:wales/wales-p02] Clog dancing was preserved and developed by Hywel Wood (1882–1967) and others who perpetuated the art on local and national stages.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Welsh Folk Dance Society was founded in 1949.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Contemporary dance grew out of Cardiff in the 1970s.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The National Dance Company Wales, formed in 1983, is now resident at the Wales Millennium Centre.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Traditional Welsh dishes include laverbread (made from *Porphyra umbilicalis*, an edible seaweed), bara brith (fruit bread), cawl (a lamb stew), cawl cennin (leek soup), and Welsh cakes.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Cockles are sometimes served as a traditional breakfast with bacon and laverbread.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Although Wales has its own traditional food and has absorbed much of the cuisine of England, Welsh diets now owe more to the countries of India, China and the United States.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Chicken tikka masala is the country's favourite dish, while hamburgers and Chinese food outsell fish and chips as takeaways.
[src:wales/wales-p02] More than 50 national governing bodies regulate and organise their sports in Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Most of those involved in competitive sports select, organise and manage individuals or teams to represent their country at international events or fixtures against other countries.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales is represented at major world sporting events such as the FIFA World Cup, Rugby World Cup, Rugby League World Cup and the Commonwealth Games.
[src:wales/wales-p02] At the Olympic Games, Welsh athletes compete alongside those of Scotland, England and Northern Ireland as part of a Great Britain team.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales has hosted several international sporting events.
[src:wales/wales-p02] These include the 1958 Commonwealth Games, the 1999 Rugby World Cup, the 2010 Ryder Cup and the 2017 UEFA Champions League Final.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Although football has traditionally been the more popular sport in North Wales, rugby union is seen as a symbol of Welsh identity and an expression of national consciousness.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Wales national rugby union team takes part in the annual Six Nations Championship and has also competed in every Rugby World Cup, hosting the tournament in 1999.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The five professional sides that replaced the traditional club sides in major competitions in 2003 were replaced in 2004 by the four regions: Cardiff Blues, Dragons, Ospreys and Scarlets.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Welsh regional teams play in the United Rugby Championship, the Heineken Champions Cup if they qualify and the European Rugby Challenge Cup, again dependent on qualification.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Rugby league in Wales dates back to 1907.
[src:wales/wales-p02] A professional Welsh League existed from 1908 to 1910.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales has had its own football league, the Welsh Premier League, since 1992.
[src:wales/wales-p02] For historical reasons, five Welsh clubs play in the English football league system: Cardiff City, Swansea City, Newport County, Wrexham, and Merthyr Town.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The country has produced a considerable number of footballers who have played at international level.
[src:wales/wales-p02] At UEFA Euro 2016, the Wales national team achieved their best ever finish, reaching the semi-finals.
[src:wales/wales-p02] In international cricket, Wales and England field a single representative team, administered by the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB), called the England cricket team, or simply 'England'.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Occasionally, a separate Wales team play limited-overs competitions.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Glamorgan County Cricket Club is the only Welsh participant in the England and Wales County Championship.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales has produced notable participants of individual sports including snooker, track and field, cycling, and boxing.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Wales is regarded as a modern Celtic nation which contributes to its national identity, with Welsh artists regularly appearing at Celtic festivals.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The red dragon is the principal symbol of national identity and pride, personifying the fearlessness of the Welsh nation.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The dragon is first referenced in literature as a symbol of the people in the Historia Brittonum.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Vortigern (Welsh: *Gwrtheyrn*), King of the Celtic Britons, is interrupted while attempting to build a fort at Dinas Emrys.
[src:wales/wales-p02] He is told by Ambrosius to dig up two dragons beneath the castle.
[src:wales/wales-p02] He discovers a red dragon representing the Celtic Britons, and a white dragon representing Anglo-Saxons.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Ambrosius prophesies that the Celtic Britons will reclaim the island and push the Anglo-Saxons back to the sea.
[src:wales/wales-p02] As an emblem, the red dragon of Wales has been used since the reign of Cadwaladr, King of Gwynedd from around 655 AD, and appears prominently on the national flag of Wales, which became an official flag in 1959.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The banner of Owain Glyndŵr is associated with Welsh nationhood; it was carried into battle by Welsh forces during Glyndŵr's battles against the English, and includes four lions on red and gold.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The standard is similar to the arms of Llywelyn ap Gruffudd (Llywelyn the Last), the last Prince of Wales before the conquest of Wales by Edward I of England.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The design may also be influenced by the arms of Glyndŵr's parents, both of whom had lions in their arms.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Owain Glyndŵr Day is celebrated on 16 September in Wales and there have been calls to make it a national bank holiday.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The Prince of Wales's feathers is also used in Wales: it consists of three white feathers emerging from a gold coronet, and the German motto *Ich dien* (I serve).
[src:wales/wales-p02] Several Welsh representative teams, including the Welsh rugby union, and Welsh regiments in the British Army, including the Royal Welsh, use the badge or a stylised version of it.
[src:wales/wales-p02] On 1 March, Welsh people celebrate Saint David's Day, commemorating the death of the country's patron saint in 589.
[src:wales/wales-p02] It is not a recognised bank holiday although there have been calls to make it so.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The day is celebrated by schools and cultural societies across Wales, and customs include the wearing of a leek or a daffodil, which are two national emblems of Wales.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Children also wear the national costume.
[src:wales/wales-p02] The origins of the leek can be traced to the 16th century, while the daffodil became popular in the 19th century, encouraged by David Lloyd George.
[src:wales/wales-p02] This is attributed to confusion (or association) between the Welsh word for leeks, *cennin*, and that for daffodils, *cennin Pedr* or St.
[src:wales/wales-p02] A report in 1916 gave preference to the leek, which has appeared on British pound coins.
[src:wales/wales-p02] Other Welsh festivals include Mabsant, when parishes would celebrate the patron saint of their local church, although this is now rarely observed, and a more modern celebration, Dydd Santes Dwynwen (St Dwynwen's Day), observed on 25 January in a similar way to St Valentine's Day.
